x = f(t) = t + \sin t, y = g(t) = \cos t, t \in [0, \pi]
L
\int_0^\pi\sqrt{(f'(t))^2+(g'(t))^2}dt = \int_0^\pi\sqrt{(1+\cos t)^2 + (-\sin t)^2}dt
\cos{t} = 2\cos^2\frac{t}{2} - 1
\sqrt{2\cdot2\cos^2{\frac{t}{2}}}\\=2\left|\cos\frac{t}{2}\right|
 (1+\cos t)^2+(-\sin t)^2=1+2\cos t+\cos^2 t+\sin^2 t=2+2\cos t=4\cos^2\big(\tfrac{t}{2}\big). 
 \sqrt{(1+\cos t)^2+(-\sin t)^2}=2\big\lvert\cos\big(\tfrac{t}{2}\big)\big\rvert. 
